<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-868-681  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 868 681.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  April 16 1990 n3155 p88(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The burning-bright future of lasers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McWilliams, Gary; Brandt, Richard; Gross, Neil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Diode lasers, now being used in compact-disc players, fiber-opticsnetworks, projection television and scalpels, may also begin toreplace larger gas lasers used for cutting, welding and otherindustrial jobs.andP;  Advances in diode laser technology have resultedin the introduction of the very powerful three-watt laser by SonyCorp and laser arrays that generate hundreds of watts for low-costcutting and welding tools.andP;  Also being developed is quantum-wiretechnology that is expected to result in an ultra-efficient laser.andO;The strides that have been achieved in laser technology also bringdown the price of diodes.andP;  Eventually, it will be possible tomanufacture small but powerful lasers by the millions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (innovations).andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   The making of a &quot;quantum wire&quot; laser. (chart)Person:    Pfeiffer, Loren (research).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>